Why would it take a complete change of PHP's semantics?  Accessing static members of classes follow C++ syntax, there's no reason why namespaces couldn't follow the same syntax and semantics.  It would break nothing in the PHP language spec.<p>namespace foo1; function bar();
class foo2 { function bar(); }<p>foo1::bar();   // Namespace call
foo2::bar();   // Static method call<p>namespace foo2;  // Syntax error; class foo2 already exists.<p>The problem is, the internals of PHP are that namespaces and classes are in different hashes and the call to either compile to entirely different byte code.  The "correct" implementation would have namespaces and classes together and both calls compile to the same code.  Now I accept that the PHP internals are perhaps too convoluted to resolve this issue but that doesn't make this any less terrible.  It's a hack solution.
